        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> However, after reading your comment, I re-evaluated how to make what I want work without any changes to your PR, and I think there is a decent solution with some precedent. The logger Serilog in C# implements async logging with a dedicated async sink that takes as a parameter a list of sinks. So to achieve what I want I could just create a dedicated sink that directs logs to multiple other sinks. Im okay with this approach.\r\n\r\nI don't mean that kind of implementation. You can check `create_writer`; `vim.Log` simply uses `self.sink:write()` there. If we need to support multiple sinks, we can just change `self.sink` to `sinks` and call `sink:write()` on each one. Supporting this natively is very simple. It's just that this PR hasn't yet exposed the interface mentioned in the description, like `vim.log.new({ name = 'my-plugin', sink = 'echo' })`. \r\n\r\n> I was mostly concerned about the typing of the sink field because changing it to an array or keyed list of sinks would likely be a breaking change.\r\n\r\nI knew this would bring potential changes and wanted to handle as many use cases as possible, so I did not expose the interface in this PR, intending to leave the discussion for later. However, If we need to support it, it's also easy to implement via overloading—making it support passing either a single sink or multiple sinks, for example: `vim.log.new({ name = 'my-plugin', sink = { 'echo', 'file' } })`.",
            "created_at": "2026-05-16T14:24:59Z",
